Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil over high heat. Halve, peel and
thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Trim
the @carrot{1}(trimmed) and halve lengthways (no need to peel). Thinly slice
widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a
#garlic press{}). Zest then halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved). Roughly
chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Chop the
@british turkey steaks{2}(chopped into 2cm chunks).

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands after handling raw meat!

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the
turkey, shallot and carrot. Stir-fry until the turkey has browned and the
veggies have started to soften, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the @pasanda style seasoning{1}
and garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

> TIP: Add less pasanda if you don't like it too spicy.

Meanwhile, when the water comes to the boil, stir in the @quinoa{120} and bring
back to the boil. Lower the heat and simmer until the quinoa has doubled in
size and the seed has visibly split, ~{12-15%minutes}. Drain into a #sieve{}
and return to the saucepan, off the heat. Cover with a #lid{} and set aside.

Add the @water for the curry{100%ml} to the curry and bring to the boil. Stir in
the @chicken stock powder{1/2} and @coconut powder{25}. Make sure you stir out
any lumps and simmer until the turkey is cooked through, the carrots are
soft and the sauce has thickened, another ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The turkey is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

When the quinoa is cooked and drained, season to taste with @salt{} and
@ground black pepper{} and stir in half the lime zest and half the coriander.
Stir the @baby spinach{125} into the curry a handful at a time to wilt it, then
stir in the remaining lime zest. Finish with a squeeze of lime juice and get
ready to serve.

Share the quinoa between your bowls and top with the turkey curry. Finish with
a sprinkling of the remaining coriander. Enjoy!